            <div id="canvas-main">
							an encoding schema where in digital data is mapped to literal words.<br><div id="Codes-Example">
	<table id="Codes-Table"><tbody><tr class="Code_Label"><td>
					Bar Code
				</td>
				<td>
					QR Code
				</td>
				<td>
					WCode
				</td>
			</tr><tr class="Code"><td>
					<img src="/resource/bar_code.png" alt="Bar Code : Rectangle with black bars"></td>
				<td>
					<img src="/resource/qr_code.png" alt="QR Code : Square with black blocks"></td>
				<td>
					<img src="/resource/w_code.png" alt="WCode : \ Cat Rock Friend Tomato /"></td>
			</tr><tr class="Code_Value"><td>
					123456
				</td>
				<td>
					http://wikipedia.org
				</td>
				<td>
					9801234567
				</td>
			</tr></tbody></table></div>
<div id="description">
	Like Bar Codes, a WCode represents a piece of digital data; But -<br>
	it is different in that: instead of using geometrical figures like bars, blocks or dots, it uses: literal words.<br><br>
	Thus, it is <strong>readable by humans</strong>; a computer is still required though, to decode data.<br><br>
	This makes it possible for WCodes to be:
	<ul><li>
			manually entered in to a computer via a keyboard.
		</li>
		<li>
			relay to another person over voice, print or handwritten and electronic text-messages.
		</li>
		<li>
			short and simple, compared to the original data.<br><table id="Comparision-Table"><caption class="indent-2">
					as in the example above:
				</caption>
				<tbody><tr><td class="t-type">
							Original:
						</td>
						<td class="t-size">
							<strong>10 Digits</strong>
						</td>
						<td>
							-
						</td>
						<td>
							<span class="content-high">Nine</span>
							<span class="content-high">Eight</span>
							<span class="content-high">Zero</span>
							<span class="content-high">One</span>
							<span class="content-high">Two</span>
							<span class="content-high">Three</span>
							<span class="content-high">Four</span>
							<span class="content-high">Five</span>
							<span class="content-high">Six</span>
							<span class="content-high">Seven</span>
						</td>
					</tr><tr><td class="t-type">
							WCode:
						</td>
						<td class="t-size">
							<strong>4 Nouns</strong>
						</td>
						<td>
							-
						</td>
						<td>
							<span class="content-high">Cat</span>
							<span class="content-high">Rock</span>
							<span class="content-high">Friend</span>
							<span class="content-high">Tomato</span>
						</td>
					</tr></tbody></table></li>
		<li>
			committed to one's memory.<br><span class="indent-2">or small portions of a long code — which aids manual entry.</span>
		</li>
	</ul>
	See the <a class="content-link XHRef" href="/video" data-xhref="Video">video</a> or <a class="content-link XHRef" href="/presentation" data-xhref="presentation">Presentation</a> for slides.<br>
	For more examples see: <a class="content-link XHRef" href="/faq" data-xhref="faq">FAQ</a>, <a class="content-link XHRef" href="/applications" data-xhref="applications">Applications</a>, <a class="content-link XHRef" href="/use-cases" data-xhref="use-cases">Use-Cases</a>.<br><br>
	Only 1024 popular, unique and phonetically distinct nouns are currently used for the words of a WCode.<br>
	As such - technically, WCode is simply Base-1024 encoding. See: <a class="content-link XHRef" href="/wordlist" data-xhref="wordlist">WordList</a> &amp; <a class="content-link XHRef" href="/recommendations" data-xhref="recommendations">Recommendations</a>.<br><br>
	Additionally:
	<ul><li>
			Due to the limited dictionary - predictive input makes manual entry in to a computer: quick and easy.<br></li>
		<li>
			A printed WCode can be read directly by a machine using camera and OCR Software.<br></li>
		<li>
			Audio WCodes could be machine-readable using: Speech Recognition technology.<br></li>
		<li>
			Picto-graphical WCodes simillar to the Japanese graphical eMoticons: <a class="content-link" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/emoji" target="_blank">eMoji</a>, may be feasible.<br></li>
	</ul><span class="indent-3">possible to:</span>
	<ul><li>
			Ensure: error free delivery of data, with checksums - that can be embedded in the WCode.
		</li>
		<li>
			Further shorten WCodes since the binary data that they represent - can be compressed.
		</li>
		<li>
			Secure end-to-end communication using cryptography algorithms like: Asymmetric-Key Encryption.
		</li>
		<li>
			Make WCodes resilient to errors - to an extent; by encrporating: Digital Error Correction techniques.
		</li>
	</ul></div>
